<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY DIGEST: LOS ALAMITOS; 
</P>
<P>
TIMETABLE FOR SCHOOL CROSSING SIGNAL ASKED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Worried about the safety of students crossing the street in front of Los 
Alamitos High School, the City Council has asked the city staff for a timetable 
on installing a traffic signal. 
</P>
<P>
The council stopped short of approving money for the Cerritos Avenue project, 
deciding a better time to do so would be in January, when the item could be 
added to the midyear budget. 
</P>
<P>
A painted crosswalk in front of the school was removed in the spring after a 
student was struck by a car while using the crosswalk. The student was not 
seriously hurt. 
</P>
<P>
The council decided the painted crosswalk was not always visible to motorists 
and gave students a "false sense of security" in crossing the street. 
</P>
<P>
Signs have been posted instead, warning students not to jaywalk, said Mike 
Brotemarkle, city community development director. Students must now cross at 
Humbolt Street or Los Alamitos Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
There is still some debate as to what sort of crossing will be used, but "that 
one design aspect" could be determined at a later date, Councilman Ronald Bates 
said at the council meeting this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
