<HEADLINE>
<P>
TELEMANN AND WAGNER OPEN CHAMBER BILLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS PASLES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Orange County Chamber Orchestra's 1989-90 season opens Nov. 5 with the 
Suite from Telemann's "Don Quichotte der Lowenritter" and Wagner's "Siegfried 
Idyll," conductor Micah Levy announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Included in the concert will be Mozart's Sinfonia Concertante in E-flat, with 
violinist Diana Halprin and violist Geraldine Walther; Faure's Berceuse in D 
for Violin and Strings, and Hindemith's "Trauermusik" for Viola and Strings. 
The program will be repeated Nov. 6. 
</P>
<P>
Sunday performances during the chamber's seventh season will be held at 4 p.m. 
at St. Joseph's Center at the Loyola Marymount University Orange Campus. Each 
program will be repeated the following Monday at 8 p.m. at South Coast 
Repertory in Costa Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
The season will continue with the following programs: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Feb. 4 and 5, 1990: Boyce's Overture in D, No. 4; Haydn's Symphony No. 82 
("The Bear"); Robert Cummings' Oboe Concerto, with soloist Allan Vogel, 
principal oboist with the Los Angeles Chamber Orchestra. Cummings is a county 
resident. 
</P>
<P>
 -- March 18 and 19: Handel's Concerto a Dui Cori, No. 3; Leopold Mozart's 
Sinfonia da Caccia; Ernest Chausson's Piano Trio, with violinist Sydney Weiss 
and pianist Jeanne Weiss; work to be announced. 
</P>
<P>
 -- May 20 and 21: Suite No. 1 from Handel's "Water Music"; Mozart's Concerto 
No. 21, with pianist Gita Karasik; Peteris Vask's "Musica Dolorsa." Vask is a 
contemporary Latvian composer. 
</P>
<P>
Information: (714) 649-2423. CHRIS PASLES 
</P>
</TEXT>
