<P>
INDUSTRIAL STATES' POPULATION GROWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The industrial states of the Midwest and Northeast are pulling out of the 
population doldrums and adding people once again, the Census Bureau reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
"The industrial-based states of Indiana, Michigan and Ohio continue to recover 
from the early 1980s population losses," the bureau said. "These three states 
added more population between 1986 and 1988 than in the previous five years 
combined." 
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Northeast's population growth between 1985 and 1988 was the 
highest since the late 1960s, the bureau said. 
</P>
<P>
The report came just one day after the bureau and the Department of Agriculture 
reported that the nation's rural population had halted its long-term decline. 
</P>
